1.  Background 
 

Under The Equality Act 2010 (Gender Pay Gap Information) Regulations 2017, 
employers with 250 or more employees, in England, Wales and Scotland are required 
to publish their overall mean and median gender pay gaps each year.  

The gender pay gap is different to equal pay.  Equal pay relates to men and women 
receiving equal pay for equal work. The gender pay gap is defined as the difference 
between the median (actual mid-point) or mean (average) basic annual earnings of men 
and women expressed as a percentage of the median or mean basic annual earning. 
See the formula for calculation Gender Pay Gap calculation below.  

 

 

 

 

 

Hourly Rate (Men) – Hourly rate (Women) 

Gender Pay Gap =     --------------------------------------------------------  X 100 

 

 

 

               Hourly Rate (Men) 

Mean    

Average (sum of hourly rates / number of employees) 

Median  

Middle value of an ordered set of data 

 

 

